  "signature": "ed25519:5a6f9f74f77d9b3db9433c1888ed4d0e43ec9f5f184cd7fc542bff4ad57c7bb68161fd01ad2dac8b12f6748fa484c6a6c36a2d7c2e585598bd906a0fed1b8000",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-full-v-and-v-plan",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is governed by a documented software quality assurance plan conforming to ISO 9001 and FDA software guidance. Version control (Git, tagged release v9.0.3), issue tracking, regression test suite (847 test cases, 100% pass rate), and release notes are archived. SQA plan reviewed and approved by independent assessor. Achieved Gradation 5: full SQA plan with independent audit trail."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl5-mms",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to all governing equations including the power-law hemolysis transport model. Observed order of accuracy matches theoretical order (p_obs = 1.97 ± 0.04 for second-order schemes) across three systematically refined grids. Unit tests for boundary conditions, turbulence model source terms, and hemolysis scalar transport verified independently. Results archived in code verification report CVR-2025-07."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-gci-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Grid convergence study performed on four systematically refined meshes (0.8M, 3.2M, 12.8M, 51.2M cells; refinement ratio r=2). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Roache (1994) for hemolysis index QoI. GCI_fine = 1.8% for hemolysis index at design point; GCI < 3% across all 5 operating conditions. Asymptotic range confirmed (GCI_coarse/GCI_fine ≈ r^p). Time-step sensitivity verified: CFL < 0.5 throughout. Discretization error budget documented in DER-2025-09."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-fda-pump-protocol",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for the FDA benchmark pump (Stewart et al. 2012) are fully documented: bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 33±2%, flow rates Q ∈ {2,3,4,5,6} L/min, rotational speeds N ∈ {2500,3500,4500,5500} RPM. All 5 COU operating points are bracketed within the experimental envelope. Temperature, viscosity, and hematocrit measurements traceable to NIST standards. Test condition report TCR-2025-03 archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-hemolysis-absolute-threshold",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental NIH measurements at all 5 COU operating points. Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) = 8.3% across operating points; maximum error = 14.1% at Q=6 L/min, N=5500 RPM. Comparison metric E_rms = 0.0021 g/100L against experimental mean ± 2σ uncertainty band. All predictions fall within expanded experimental uncertainty (k=2). Validation metric assessment documented in OCR-2025-11."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-nih-clinical-threshold",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH, g/100L), which directly maps to the clinical acceptance threshold of NIH < 0.1 g/100L established in ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, scalar stress exposure history) are directly linked to the power-law hemolysis model inputs. Traceability matrix from model output to clinical endpoint documented in QoI relevance assessment QRA-2025-05."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-cou2-mapping",
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same device class and hemodynamic regime as the COU VAD. Operating conditions in validation experiments span the full COU operating envelope. Blood analog fluid properties matched to within 5% of clinical VAD operating conditions. Geometry fidelity: identical impeller topology. Validation relevance matrix VRM-2025-08 documents factor-by-factor COU alignment with Gradation 5 justification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-iterative-convergence-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via normalized residuals for all transported quantities. Residuals reduced by 6 orders of magnitude (10^-6) for continuity and momentum; hemolysis scalar residual < 10^-8. Iterative error estimated via Richardson extrapolation on iteration count: iterative error < 0.01% of discretization error budget. Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic verification. Solver error report SER-2025-06 archived with all convergence histories."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-independent-review-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Independent analyst reproduced all 5 COU simulations from documented inputs (geometry, boundary conditions, solver settings) without access to original analyst's setup files. Results agreed to within 0.3% on NIH predictions, confirming absence of undocumented analyst-specific choices. Simulation setup checklist (35 items) completed and signed by two independent reviewers. Use error assessment documented in UER-2025-10."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-turbulence-hemolysis-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessed for both turbulence closure (k-ω SST vs. k-ε RNG vs. LES) and hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen et al. 1990 vs. Zhang et al. 2011 vs. Taskin et al. 2012). Turbulence model comparison: NIH predictions span ±12% across models; k-ω SST selected based on superior agreement with PIV data (E_rms = 0.031 m/s vs. 0.048 m/s for k-ε). Hemolysis model comparison: Giersiepen coefficients yield conservative (higher) NIH estimates. Model form uncertainty contribution = 9.2% of total NIH uncertainty budget. Documented in MFR-2025-12."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-uq-mrl5-monte-carlo",
      "rationale": "All uncertain model inputs characterized with probability distributions: blood viscosity μ ~ N(3.5, 0.3) mPa·s; hematocrit Hct ~ N(33, 2)%; hemolysis power-law exponents (α, β) from published literature meta-analysis (n=12 studies). Monte Carlo UQ with 10,000 LHS samples propagated through CFD surrogate (Kriging, R²=0.997). 95th percentile NIH = 0.072 g/100L, well below clinical threshold. Sobol first-order indices: α dominates (S1=0.61), followed by μ (S1=0.22). Input uncertainty report IUR-2025-04 archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-statistical-power-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis dataset comprises n=45 independent test runs across 5 operating points (9 replicates per point) using fresh bovine blood from 9 separate donors. Statistical power analysis confirms 90% power to detect 15% difference in NIH at α=0.05. Inter-donor variability characterized (CV = 8.3%). Sample size justification documented per ASTM F1841. Test sample assessment report TSR-2025-02 archived with donor provenance records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-cou2-validation-mapping",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between validation experiment inputs and COU simulation inputs assessed for all 12 identified input parameters. Reynolds number matching: Re_validation = 4,200–18,600 spans Re_COU = 5,100–16,800. Womersley number: Wo < 0.1 in both contexts (quasi-steady assumption valid). Blood rheology: Casson model parameters calibrated to same hematocrit range. Geometric equivalency: validation pump and COU pump share identical impeller diameter (52 mm) and blade count (5). Equivalency matrix EQM-2025-01 documents all 12 parameters with quantitative similarity metrics."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/vv40-credibility-panel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed at Gradation 5, meeting or exceeding the required levels for Model Risk Level 5. The evidence chain is complete: (1) Software quality assurance is documented with independent audit; (2) Code verification via MMS confirms second-order accuracy; (3) Discretization error GCI < 3% across all operating points; (4) Test conditions are fully characterized and NIST-traceable; (5) Output comparison shows MAPE = 8.3% with all predictions within experimental uncertainty bands; (6) QoI relevance is established via direct mapping to ISO 10993-4 clinical threshold; (7) Validation activities are directly relevant to the COU geometry and operating envelope; (8) Numerical solver error is negligible relative to discretization error; (9) Use error is excluded by independent reproduction study; (10) Model form uncertainty is quantified at 9.2% of NIH budget with conservative model selection; (11) Model inputs are characterized with Monte Carlo UQ (10,000 samples) yielding 95th percentile NIH = 0.072 g/100L, 28% below clinical threshold; (12) Test sample statistical power is adequate (90% power, n=45); (13) Input parameter equivalency is confirmed quantitatively for all 12 parameters. The combined uncertainty budget (model form + input uncertainty + discretization error) yields an expanded uncertainty of ±18% on NIH predictions (k=2), maintaining the upper bound well below the 0.1 g/100L clinical threshold. The credibility assessment panel unanimously accepts this model for the COU2 intended use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
